Our first full video from @waltdisneyworld is up on my YouTube channel!

I know Disney isn‚Äôt everyone‚Äôs cup of tea and that‚Äôs fine, we‚Äôre all different at the end of the day, but for us it‚Äôs our happy place, somewhere we return to year after year to experience the magic, there‚Äôs nothing like it in our eyes. It‚Äôs like being in a bubble, away from reality. By no means do we have a terrible life but we all have our demons and for me Disney is the perfect place to escape and forget them. And as you can always see in our Disney videos I have quite the emotional connection, it‚Äôs something that spans from my childhood, I can‚Äôt explain it, it just feels like home. We‚Äôre now in our early 30‚Äôs and have no kids but this makes no difference, we always have the most incredible time. I don‚Äôt really believe in a lot of things, but I do believe in Disney magic ‚ú®

AD - apparently üëáüèº
Are you ready for a discussion? Read on...
Ok guys so here‚Äôs the deal right now, the CMA & ASA have just released new guidelines for us online folk that we now call influencers (aka Bloggers, Instagrammers, YouTubers and Celebrities). I agree with some of the new guidelines and I do try to be as open and transparent about my content as possible because honesty is the best policy but there are other guidelines which I think are a festering pile of shite and will actually lead to more confusion for you guys, the consumers. 
So, in a nutshell here‚Äôs what I‚Äôm/we‚Äôre now expected to do in order to ‚Äòplay by the rules‚Äô.
1. Any content you see from me which includes a gifted item from one or multiple brands (tagged or not tagged) must be marked as AD (or ADVERT, but only one of those 2 terms) and it must be right at the start of the post (across any and all channels; blog, Instagram, Youtube etc etc).
2. Even if I‚Äôve bought an item myself but have previously worked with that brand on either a paid or gifting basis or even if I‚Äôve just been to one of their events, it must also be marked as AD and the relationship I have with the brand must be explained in the caption/description box/text.
3. Any use of affiliate links anywhere must be marked (again) as AD whether an item has been bought with my own money, gifted, loaned, inherited, found on the side of the road and so forth.

So essentially 95% of posts/content you see from me (and probably most other ‚Äúinfluencers‚Äù) should be marked as AD which to me seems to defeat the object in determining what is actually ‚Äòpaid‚Äô. But I‚Äôd like to hear what you guys think about all this, so whether you‚Äôre a fellow ‚Äúinfluencer‚Äù or if you‚Äôre someone who consumes online content, the floor is yours üëçüèº Just to clarify, for those of you who can‚Äôt be arsed to scroll through all the comments ü§£ I‚Äôm on board with being transparent, I think it‚Äôs incredibly important in this industry to disclaim what‚Äôs been paid for a what‚Äôs been gifted. I just think it should be AD and GIFTED rather than all AD üëçüèº

There‚Äôs a new vlog up on my YouTube channel today with a huuuge wardrobe clear out & re-organising sesh üôåüèº but there‚Äôs something that I would like to touch on... ‚Ä¢‚Ä¢‚Ä¢
I love what I do, and I count myself to be incredibly lucky that I get to do what I love everyday. I like to keep my feet (and butt üôä) firmly planted on the ground, and yes I earn more money now than I used to working in retail but I definitely work for it. However I‚Äôm becoming increasingly aware that the pressures of Instagram and this social world can have a negative impact on some of you, and I just want to remind you all that the majority of influencers/bloggers/youtubers (myself included) don‚Äôt live a ‚Äònormal life‚Äô. Don‚Äôt compare yourselves to us, don‚Äôt get yourself in financial trouble try to keep up with our spending habits, I want you to know the reality of it. I can‚Äôt speak for everyone but my shopping habits are 10x that of a ‚Äònormal person‚Äô. I see myself as a product tester, I‚Äôm always honest about the items that I buy or items I‚Äôm gifted. I‚Äôll give you the pros and cons, because all I want to do is help you guys find the best bits. Not all of you will like everything that I feature across my channels which is why I feature so many different items and different brands/retailers. I‚Äôm a people pleaser, I like to make sure there‚Äôs something for everyone and every budget but still in line with my own style and taste, because fashion is for EVERYONE. I also love an outfit change and sometimes I‚Äôll get changed twice a day for different things, why? Because I just love fashion, it‚Äôs the way I express myself and how I keep myself inspired.  I‚Äôm here to inspire you guys, or at least I hope so, but please don‚Äôt get sucked in to the un-reality of this world ‚ù§Ô∏è #EHsneakerdiaries

My top 4 travel essentials when heading to warmer climates:
1. Vintage Levis shorts. I have about 12 pairs now but I love them and you can pick them up super cheap on eBay & Etsy. The sizing is old school because they‚Äôre vintage so to give you an idea, I take a 30 in my vintage Levi‚Äôs.
2. Shirts...lots of shirts. Long, oversized, linen, striped, plain, printed (not too jazzy mind). I love to layer them over swimwear for on the beach or around the pool, and for tucking into those vintage Levi‚Äôs. Linen ones are breathable and light and are perfect for protecting your skin from the sun üëçüèº
3. Basic swimwear. I often go for black, I‚Äôm not about bold or bright prints, just something basic that will go with everything. I also don‚Äôt pack hundreds, just 1 or 2. On this trip I only packed 1 bikini and 1 swimsuit, that‚Äôs often all I need üòä
4. Shades üòé. I wear them all year round so that one will be no surprise to you guys üòÇ I have a slight obsession with sunglasses and I buy way too many, mainly Celine & Rayban which are my go-to sunglasses brands.
